post_text: Due to the quickly evolving nature of the COVID-19 pandemic, the increasing number of COVID-19 positive cases, and our desire to communicate with families as soon as possible, Superintendent Ryan Noss has made the decision that Corvallis School District students will participate in remote learning for the first six weeks of the school year. We will evaluate returning in-person to schools after that time and will reopen school buildings when it is safe to do so. For more information, visit https://www.csd509j.net/news/2020-21-school-year-to-begin-with-remote-learning-for-all-students/

2020-21 School Year to Begin with Remote Learning for All Students - Corvallis School District
text:
Due to the quickly evolving nature of the COVID-19 pandemic, the increasing number of COVID-19 positive cases, and our desire to communicate with families as soon as possible, Superintendent Ryan Noss has made the decision that Corvallis School District students will participate in remote learning for the first six weeks of the school year. We will evaluate returning in-person to schools after that time and will reopen school buildings when it is safe to do so. For more information, visit https://www.csd509j.net/news/2020-21-school-year-to-begin-with-remote-learning-for-all-students/

post_text: Ava Carey has been found and is safe!
shared_text:
City of Corvallis Police Department
August 29 at 3:39 PM ·

AVA CAREY HAS BEEN FOUND AND IS SAFE

The Corvallis Police Department is pleased to announce that Ava Carey has been located and is safe in a neighboring state.

The Corvallis Police Department and the family wish to thank the community for the outpouring of support and assistance in locating Ava, who has been missing since August 20th.

The Corvallis Police Department would like to acknowledge and than the agencies of the Benton County Major Crimes Team (The Albany Police Department, the Philomath Police Department, the Benton County Sheriff's Office, The Linn County Sheriff's Office, the Benton County District Attorney's Office, the local FBI and their Child Abduction Rapid Deployment Team for their tireless efforts in this past week to locate Ava safe.

The family wishes for privacy at this time.

shared_text:
City of Corvallis Police Department
August 26 at 8:27 AM ·

*********** UPDATE: FOUND SAFE ****************

Update for August 26th –

Yesterday, officers utilized our Major Crash Team drone to survey green spaces near Village Green Park. Officers and investigators also followed up on over fifty tips we have received and more tips are still coming in. These tips are important to our efforts in finding Ava, and we thank the community for calling and emailing those tips in.

To assist with our reception and processing of these tips, we have established a tip line, which is staffed 24 hours a day, and can be reached by calling our Dispatch center at 541-766-6911.

As the investigation continues, we are continuing our work with the assistance of the Benton County Sheriff’s Office, FBI, and the Benton County District Attorney’s Office.

post_text: We would like to thank our community as you have done an amazing job of coming around the Carey family in support and service. If you have seen Ava since August 20th at 5:00 PM, please call the dispatch center 541-766-6911.
shared_text:
City of Corvallis Police Department
August 24 at 1:45 PM ·

*********** UPDATE: FOUND SAFE ****************

Update for August 24th –

Officers have been pursuing leads as we receive them by phone, email and via social media. These leads have been helpful in our establishment of a timeline surrounding Ava’s disappearance, but we still need the communities help to fill in gaps.

As we continue to formulate our timeline, we would request anyone with pertinent information please call the Corvallis Police Department rather than post the information in our social media comments. Though we are monitoring social media, the volume of responses and outpouring of support for the Carey family could lead to us missing an important tip.

When leaving a tip please include your name and phone number so officers can contact you if we have questions or need clarification.

If you have seen her since she left home on August 20th, please call our dispatch center 541-766-6924. We do ask you call only if you have information that may help find Ava; calling for status updates or other information only tie up resources we could be using to find Ava.

post_text: After a year of listening and learning, the Regional Racial Equity Group has drafted and signed a proclamation acknowledging a commitment to build an educational system that addresses institutional racism and empowers, honors, and celebrates the cultures and identities of our diverse student population, empowering their voices and perspectives as shared partners in the educational system. While there is uncertainty ahead while we make plans for the 2020-21 school year, this proclamation will be a guiding force as we move forward and will be used to hold the member organizations accountable to actively pursue racial equity. Thank you to the NAACP Corvallis/Albany chapter and our neighboring districts for their partnership in this work. For more information, visit https://www.csd509j.net/news/regional-racial-equity-group-signs-proclamation-as-a-call-to-action/
shared_text:

Regional Racial Equity Group Signs Proclamation as a Call to Action - Corvallis School District
text:
After a year of listening and learning, the Regional Racial Equity Group has drafted and signed a proclamation acknowledging a commitment to build an educational system that addresses institutional racism and empowers, honors, and celebrates the cultures and identities of our diverse student population, empowering their voices and perspectives as shared partners in the educational system. While there is uncertainty ahead while we make plans for the 2020-21 school year, this proclamation will be a guiding force as we move forward and will be used to hold the member organizations accountable to actively pursue racial equity. Thank you to the NAACP Corvallis/Albany chapter and our neighboring districts for their partnership in this work. For more information, visit https://www.csd509j.net/news/regional-racial-equity-group-signs-proclamation-as-a-call-to-action/

May 28 at 1:37 PM ·

Assistance League members delivered supplies from our Hygiene Help philanthropy to the CSD Welcome Center on 35th street in Corvallis. A delivery of toilet paper, toothbrushes and toothpaste, feminine hygiene products, dishwashing soap, laundry soap and deodorant were passed along. It is a great way to partner with the school district to get supplies to families in need. Member Jan Baumgartner does turn some heads when she shops for that much toilet paper!

post_text: Corvallis School District counselor Nichole Hoffman is here to share how practicing gratitude can help us stay mentally and emotionally healthy. On this Memorial Day, a day where people often travel and remember past family members, remember that we are trying to remain physically distant but emotionally connected. Looking through photos can be helpful to remind adults and kids that there have been good times. You can also start a gratitude journal of your own or share a virtual meal with a distant family member. Right now, especially during a holiday, it's important to take a break from routine to play and connect. #MentalHealthMondays

post_text: Amanda McBride, nominated by her work bestie Kira Mudd, is a true rock star of CSD! "Amanda and I were both pregnant over the 2019 school year and both went on maternity leave around winter break. Having another person to share that experience with was so important to me. On the hard days, she kept me going. She cares about the welfare of her students and worries deeply about the ones she hasn’t heard from. She is a true gem and deserves so much gratitude and beauty from the world. Her students are lucky to have this teacher in their corner and I am lucky to have her as a friend." #WeAreCSD

text:
Reading Rainbow is being reinvented with a social media twist. @LeVarBurton is live streaming story time on Twitter for kids of all ages. Mondays at 9AM he reads a children's book. Wednesdays at 3 PM is for teens. Fridays at 6 PM is an adult title. Tune in tonight for the first one for grownups! The videos from earlier this week are still showing in the feed. Not on Twitter? No problem! A Twitter account is not necessary to view the videos. #LevarBurtonReads
-----
Leyendo arcoiris (Reading Rainbow) se está reinventando con un giro para las redes sociales. La lectura de cuentos de @LeVarBurton se está transmitiendo en vivo en Twitter para niños de todas las edades. Los lunes a las 9AM el lee un libro para niños. Los miércoles a las 3 PM es para adolescentes. Los viernes a las 6 PM es un título para adultos. ¡Sintonice esta noche para la primera entrega para adultos! Los vídeos de principios de esta semana todavía se muestran bajo demanda. ¿No estás en Twitter? ¡No hay problema! No es necesaria una cuenta de Twitter para ver los videos. #LevarBurtonReads

On April 14, the National Ambassador for Young People’s Literature, Jason Reynolds, is launching GRAB THE MIC: Tell Your Story in collaboration with the Library of Congress, the Children’s Book Council, and Every Child a Reader. The program will include biweekly videos and a monthly newsletter. Jason Reynolds is an amazing and inspiring author and speaker. This is sure to be wonderful! See the Resource Guide at: https://guides.loc.gov/jason-reynolds/grab-the-mic -- Dana
-----
El 14 de abril, el embajador nacional de la literatura para jóvenes, Jason Reynolds, estará lanzando el proyecto TOMA EL MICRÓFONO; CUENTA TU HISTORIA (GRAB THE MIC: Tell Your Story) en colaboración con la biblioteca del congreso, el consejo de libros infantiles y cada niño lector. El programa incluye videos 2 veces por semana y un boletín informativo mensual. Jason Reynolds es un autor y conferencista impresionante. ¡Seguro que esto será maravilloso! Revisa la guía de recursos en: https://guides.loc.gov/jason-reynolds/grab-the-mic -- Dana

Starting April 7, stadium lights have been turned on at 8:20 pm on school nights to honor our students. This week, we have been lighting up the stadium for one minute for each day schools are closed during this pandemic. Starting next week, the lights will be turned on at 8:20 pm and illuminated for 20 minutes on a random school night of the week for the remainder of the school year. We do not encourage people to come to the stadium and staff will be monitoring that groups are not gathering. #bethelightOR
-----
Iniciando el 7 de abril, las luces del estadio se han estado encendiendo a las 8:20 pm en las noches escolares para honrar a nuestros estudiantes. Esta semana, hemos estado iluminando el estadio durante un minuto por cada día que las escuelas estén cerradas durante esta pandemia. A partir de la próxima semana, las luces se encenderán a las 8:20 pm durante 20 minutos en una noche escolar aleatoria durante la semana por el resto del año escolar. No alentamos a las personas a acudir al estadio y el personal estará monitoreando que no haya personas reuniéndose. #selaluzOR

post_text: Last spring, we began plans for the removal of the CHS rock due to an increase in offensive graffiti on the rock, including profane, racist, homophobic, anti-Semitic, and sexist messages. While this work was scheduled for the summer, the removal of the rock had moved to this week due to a number of schedule changes and the cancellation of school. This morning, Principal Matt Boring met virtually with senior class and ASB presidents, and their leadership advisor. The discussion included the idea of a new rock, one placed in the courtyard outside the cafeteria. This location acknowledges current reality — the rock needs to be in a more secure location–and ties into past tradition — the rock was located in the courtyard at the old CHS. There is great symbolism in placing a new rock this year and having the class of 2020 tied to something that is solid and strong. This class is showing and will continue to show resilience through a senior year that has been upended in unprecedented ways. Go Sparts!

Thank you to CSD school counselor Nichole Hoffman for some GREAT suggestions for students! Here is some helpful information that Nichole would like to share!

Write a letter to your teacher
Write in your journal
Make a fort in your living room

Read or listen to audio books
Write a movie script or a play script and act out the parts

Thank you Nichole!

What is social distancing?

You’re going to keep hearing the term “social distancing” as we work together to slow the spread of COVID-19. Put simply, it means keeping your distance from other people in order to keep from catching or spreading a virus.

This could mean leaving several feet of personal space between you and other people as well as strategies like working from home, hosting meetings virtually instead of in person, and cancelling large events.

COVID-19 is in our communities, and now our primary goal is to slow its spread. Review the Governor's prevention strategies for COVID-19 at: http://ow.ly/eec150yLhOh

post_text:
March 12, 2020 COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Update: All families will receive an email update on Thursday, March 12 with this update. Following the announcement by Governor Kate Brown, suspension of non-essential school-based activities and after-school activities begins this week, and will remain in effect until further notice. This includes the suspension of all assemblies and events, group parent meetings, OSAA competitions, off-campus field trips, and professional development meetings and events. We are still planning to host school conferences on March 12 and 13. School principals and office managers will be in contact with staff and parents/guardians with updates about conference logistics. We are working closely with the Benton County Health Department, Oregon Health Authority and following Oregon Department of Education guidelines to take every step possible so that we can continue to provide high-quality education for all of our students and keep our schools open.
https://www.csd509j.net/news/health-update-for-families/

post_text: October 29, 2019: At approximately 2:25 pm, Linus Pauling MS was evacuated due to the smell of smoke. The Corvallis Fire Department responded quickly. After evacuating the building, teachers took attendance and supervised students at the evacuation area. The cause of the smell was determined to be related to the HVAC system which has now been turned off. There was no fire and district facilities staff are working on the HVAC system. The school day will end at the regular time. Buses will follow their regular schedules.

Students in Corvallis are organizing a walkout during the school day to show their support and will gather again outside the gates of the Friday evening CHS/CVHS football game at Corvallis High School. Climate walkout activities are not school or district-sponsored events. The Corvallis School District Board Policy JFI allows for student demonstrations that are scheduled with building administration in advance and that do not disrupt classroom activities. Absences are not excused.

Students are not required to participate and instruction will continue during any walkout event. District staff will provide supervision for on-site student safety. We understand that some adults may wish to show their support for students and for this issue, and we ask them to gather on sidewalks or public spaces rather than on school property. Those choosing to go on campus or enter a school building will be required to follow our visitor/volunteer sign-in process.

post_text: Late this morning, local law enforcement responded to an incident across the street from the main entrance at CHS. The police department requested that the school go into a lockdown. CHS immediately followed the LOCKDOWN safety protocol. The situation was resolved within 10 minutes and we are back to our regular school routine. At no time was there any threat inside the school or on CHS property. With all lockout or lockdown procedures, we are always in contact with the Corvallis Police Department to review the incident. Thank you to our staff and students for following our safety protocols. We appreciate the support from the Corvallis Police Department.

UPDATE: Lincoln Elementary is no longer in LOCKOUT.

This morning at approximately 9 am, we were made aware of law enforcement activity in close proximity to the south of Lincoln Elementary. Students were kept inside for morning recess and our staff are taking extra safety precautions. Lincoln is currently in LOCKOUT, meaning all exterior doors are locked and students will be kept inside for recess. School is operating as usual. We are in communication with the Corvallis Police Department and we anticipate that the situation will be resolved before school release time today.

Students were kept inside for morning recess and our staff are taking extra safety precautions. Lincoln is currently in LOCKOUT, meaning all exterior doors are locked and students will be kept inside for recess. School is operating as usual. We are in communication with the Corvallis Police Department and we anticipate that the situation will be resolved before school release time today.
